[joeyecho101]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Wait for the flash</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/KozpBHO</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/wCZ7cBO.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Czesława Kwoka was born on 15 August 1928; this picture was taken in late 1942. A Polish Catholic, her and her mother Katarzyna were transported to the Auschwitz-Birkenau complex following Aktion Zamosc, an attempt by Nazi Germany to ethnically cleanse the Polish region of Zamosc in order to facilitate later German colonisation.

One aspect of the Nazi myth of German victimhood that powered and justified the Nazi worldview alleged that German families, and in particular children, who lived in Poland following the post-World War One re-creation of that state were forcibly Polonised as part of a campaign of German cultural erasure. 

To "counteract" this, Nazi Germany operated a vast program of child abduction across occupied Poland - about 30,000 is the usual estimate. Children considered "Germanic"-seeming enough were passed to adoption agencies in Germany. The process of a child being 'confirmed' in their Germanness inevitably resulted in children who, 'on closer inspection' were not found German enough for quack Nazi eugenicists.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/ayN7JX6.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>[Picture: Rollcall in Kinder KZ Lodz.]

This led to the creation of Kinder KZ Lindmannstadt - Children's Concentration Camp Lodz - a fenced-off part of the Lodz Jewish Ghetto for these "not German enough" children, where they became part of the forced labour force of the Ghetto. 

Polish children caught engaging in petty crimes, or found to be homeless, potentially due to the arrest or execution of their parents or simply found without adult supervision during 'sweeps' by Nazi forces - were also confined in the Kinder KZ; there exist excruciating letters from children in the camp to their parents and carers. 20,000 children would be confined there in the Nazi state's only child-only concentration camp. 

A sub-camp existed outside the city at Dzierżązna, filled only with girls who produced food for the city camp. SS Aufseherin Sydomia Bayer (1903-executed 1945) killed at least one little girl at the camp, 13-year-old Urszula Kaczmarek, by either flogging her to death, or allowing her to be left in the snow outside the camp's building until she succumbed to the elements. It is probable that these conflicting records represent either two incidents in the abuse of one girl, or two separate murders of which one remains unidentified.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/NBhyuUN.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>[Picture: Elzbieta Konarska, confined in Lodz Children's Concentration Camp on 14 September 1943. Her fate is unknown.]

Czesława Kwoka was evidently not considered 'Germanic' enough for abduction, nor considered young enough for sending to Lodz, and so was condemned to immediate removal to Auschwitz-Birkenau. She died seven months after arrival at the camp on 12 March 1943, aged 14. 

There are conflicting reports of Czesława's death, it is possible she was killed by an experimental injection of phenol (a disinfectant) into her heart in one of the first human experiments overseen by newly-arrived Doctor Josef Mengele (1911-1979). The photographer who took her picture recalled that Czesława was hit across the face with a truncheon shortly before the picture was taken, hence her split lip.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/6Pv1ek8.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>[Picture: An unknown Dutch Jehovah's Witness, inmate number 25 563]

Her picture was taken by Wilhelm Brasse (1917-2012), a Polish man of German ethnicity who had been a photographer before the war and spoke German; having refused to cooperate with the new German authority's attempts to racially classify him he was arrested and deported to Auschwitz. He was consequently forced into the Politische Abteilung Erkennungsdienst ("Political Department Identification Service") of Auschwitz - the photography unit which took "mugshots" of arrivals into Auschwitz, as well as general documenting of camp operations. 

Concentration camps operated nominally as if they were prisons, as they were before some were tasked primarily with murder. Consequently, bureaucratic procedural inertia meant they kept detailed records of inmates for the purpose of maximising productivity and security, for example if an inmate escaped, their mugshot could be circulated. (There were 928 known escapes from Auschwitz, including Konstanty Jagiełło (1916-1944), who was killed during a subsequent Polish resistance attempt to release more prisoners, and one prisoner uprising by the Crematoria IV Sonderkommando.)</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/Jbc8LZq.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>[Picture: Still image from a Soviet film of survivors of Auschwitz following liberation by the Red Army; this picture includes Tomasz Szwarz; Alicja Gruenbaum; Solomon Rozalin; Gita Sztrauss; Wiera Sadler; Marta Wiess; Boro Eksztein; Josef Rozenwaser; Rafael Szlezinger; Gabriel Nejman; Adek Apfelbaum; Hillik (later Harold) Apfelbaum; Mark Berkowitz (a twin); Pesa Balter; Rut Muszkies (later Webber); Miriam Friedman; and twins Miriam Mozes & Eva Mozes wearing knitted hats. Twins were a particular area of interest in human experimentation at Auschwitz.]

The Auschtwitz photography unit was led by SS-Hauptscharführer Bernhard Walter (1911-1979) and deputy director SS-Unterscharführer Ernst Hofmann (1901-?); its manpower was mainly made up of prisoners, led by Franz Maltz, a German inmate. They each existed in a tenuous manner, kept alive for their skills, but functionally unable to act in any independent way for fear of their lives.

Prisoners forced to used their skills to document the camp's operations besides Wilhelm Brasse (prisoner number 3444) include Tadeusz Brodka (245), Eugeniusz Dembek (63764), Edward Josefsberg, Bronisław Jureczek (26672), Roman Karwat (5959), Leonid Koren (21953), Tadeusz Krzysica (120557), Tadeusz Myszkowski (593), Zdzisław Pazio (3078), Jozef Pysz (1420), Jozef Swiatloch (3529), Stanisław Tralka (660), Wladyslaw Wawrzyniak (9449), and Alfred Woycicki (39247).</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/1d7Alkw.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>[Picture: Aron Lwi, born 15 April 1879, a Jewish merchant from Zakow - he arrived in Auschwitz on 5 March 1942 as prisoner 26406. He died in the camp 5 days later, at the age of 62. ]

Hauptscharfuhrer Walter himself took several photographs in an album now known as the "Auschwitz Album", which was seemingly an attempt to create a kind of "day in the life of Auschwitz" pictoral history of the Auschwitz extermination process when it was dealing with an unusually large number of arrivals after the mass deportation of Hungarian Jews from May-July 1944, when over 400,000 people were sent to Auschwitz, prompting the Nazis to 'steamline' the camp's induction process even further to cope with the numbers arriving.

Consisting of around 200 photographs, of which 193 survive, the album shows every aspect of camp induction operations, from the arrival of predominantly Jews by train, the robbery of their property, and their division into slave labourers and those to be immediately killed.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/wUBhNl0.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>[Picture: Peter Siedielnikow; inmate number 84893]

The Auschwitz Album was discovered in a cupboard inside the SS barracks at Dora Concentration Camp - 400 miles away from Auschwitz - by Lili Jacob (1926-1999), a former inmate of Auschwitz, while the former barracks was being used as a hospital following liberation. A great many of the most well-known images of the Holocaust are from this album. The sequence of events that led to this unique record of Nazi criminality surviving are unknown.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/9V07lmt.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>[Picture: Janina Olszynska, prisoner number 8558; born August 12 1892, her, her husband, and son were arrested for being part of the Polish Resistance and sent to Auschwitz on 11 July 1942. Janina and her son Jan both survived Auschwitz; her husband Bolesław did not.]

At Auschwitz, as the Red Army approached, prisoner-photographers Walter Brasse and Bronisław Jureczek of the photography unit were ordered to burn the images of prisoners and other records. By careful packing of the stove they were using for this, ensuring it'd starve of oxygen and go out, and scattering vast amounts of photographs and negatives to create too big a job to tidy up, they allowed 38,000 photographs to survive and be collected once the Red army liberated the camp.

Wilhelm Brasse struggled to continue with photography after World War Two. His memories and testimony were crucial in several post-war trials of Nazis. He and the other surviving inmates of the photography unit had the unique distinction of being victims of the Holocaust, witnesses of the Holocaust, recorders of the Holocaust, and some of the earliest to grasp the full scale of what the Final Solution was, as they processed and developed records of crimes they'd not themselves been witness to.

You can view the whole Auschwitz album here: https://www.yadvashem.org/yv/en/exhibitions/album_auschwitz/index.asp

The photo of Czesława Kwoka, originally black and white in the archive of Memorial Oświęcim, was coloured by Mirek Szponar, and inspired this post. http://www.mirekszponar.pl/</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/KozpBHO</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[BodicaRexVII]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Elect a working class congress</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/3k1be8n</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/qT77E6n.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/3k1be8n</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[mfrybeasley]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>The struggle is real.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/1z5PiAr</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/SrV7cbZ.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/1z5PiAr</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[WakeUp2Yourself]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>She's 58 BTW...</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/3btt7rq</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/qEQ7oIQ.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/3btt7rq</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[zorrofox12]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Repost. Because Never Forget This Is What 74m Americans Voted For</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/mVJDRKF</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/0PNKbCh.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/ZjCu563.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2015/11/22/donald-trumps-outrageous-claim-that-thousands-of-new-jersey-muslims-celebrated-the-911-attacks/</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/hDHnwT7.jpg" style="max-width: